03889nam a22004935i 9780773586000DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20112011xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735860007 a10.1515/97807735860002doi  a(DE-B1597)657880  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a307.7609714/28090341 aOlson, Sherry, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPeopling the North American City :bMontreal, 1840-1900 /cPatricia Thornton, Sherry Olson. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (544 p.) :b26 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCarleton Library Series ;v22200tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tTables -- tAcknowledgments -- tCredits -- tTrajectories -- tTracking a Population -- tThe Drawing Power of the City -- tThe Hazards of City Living -- tThe Pace of Family Formation -- tThe Marriage Partnership in Context -- tEmerging Opportunities in the Urban Economy -- tFacing Risk: The Elastic Household -- tA Geography of Encounter -- tCity Folks in Their Rural Contexts -- tThe Social Emotions and the Social Fabric -- tToward a Dynamic of Cultural Coexistence -- tAppendices -- tMeasures -- tData Collection and Record Matching -- tTables -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex to Persons -- tIndex to Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBenefiting from Montreal's remarkable archival records, Sherry Olson and Patricia Thornton use an ingenious sampling of twelve surnames to track the comings and goings, births, deaths, and marriages of the city's inhabitants. The book demonstrates the importance of individual decisions by outlining the circumstances in which people decided where to move, when to marry, and what work to do. Integrating social and spatial analysis, the authors provide insights into the relationships among the city's three cultural communities, show how inequalities of voice, purchasing power, and access to real property were maintained, and provide first-hand evidence of the impact of city living and poverty on families, health, and futures. The findings challenge presumptions about the cultural "assimilation" of migrants as well as our understanding of urban life in nineteenth-century North America. The culmination of twenty-five years of work, Peopling the North American City is an illuminating look at the humanity of cities and the elements that determine whether their citizens will thrive or merely survive.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAssimilation (Sociology)zQuébec (Province)zMontréalxHistoryy19th century. 0aCity and town lifezQuébec (Province)zMontréalxHistoryy19th century. 0aImmigrant familieszQuébec (Province)zMontréalxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aThornton, Patricia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358600040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773586000423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773586000/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles